{{Infobox noble | name = Omi Sayama no Mikoto | image = | image_size = | caption = | era = [[Kofun period]] | birth_date = Unknown | death_date = Unknown | other_names = Nakatomi no Ōsayama no Mikoto, Omi Sayama | honorary_title = | deity_name = | posthumous_name = | burial_place = | rank = | lord = [[Emperor Keikō]], {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|日本武尊|1=Yamato Takeru|lt=Prince Yamato Takeru|3=ヤマトタケル|12=draft|12=draft}} | clan = {{ill|Nakatomi clan|ja|中臣氏|12=draft|12=draft}} | parents = Father: {{ill|Kunimoro no Ōkashima no Mikoto|ja|国摩大鹿島命|12=draft|12=draft}} | children = {{ill|Rai Daijin no Mikoto|ja|雷大臣命|12=draft|12=draft}} }}
'''Omi Sayama no Mikoto''' (臣狭山命) was an ancient Japanese noble from the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, regarded as an ancestor of the {{ill|Nakatomi clan|ja|中臣氏|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Overview ==
The name appears with variations in historical texts, including '''Nakatomi no Ōsayama no Mikoto''' (中臣巨狭山命) in the *{{ill|Hitachi no Kuni Fudoki|ja|常陸国風土記|12=draft|12=draft}}* and '''Omi Sayama''' (意美佐夜麻) in the *{{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|12=draft|12=draft}}*.<ref>"Emperor Kanmu, July 16, 781," *Shoku Nihongi*, vol. 36.</ref>
In the *Hitachi no Kuni Fudoki*, Omi Sayama no Mikoto is associated with the origin of the sacred boat ritual of {{ill|Kashima Shrine|ja|鹿島神宮|12=draft|12=draft}}. During the reign of {{ill|Emperor Keikō|ja|景行天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, the deity {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武甕槌命|12=draft|12=draft}} instructed Omi Sayama no Mikoto to prepare a sacred boat. Following the divine instructions, he constructed three new boats over two jō (about 6 meters) in length and offered them to the emperor. The text describes a mystical encounter in which the boat appeared alternately on land and sea, reinforcing his reverence for the deity.
In the *Shoku Nihongi*, Omi Sayama no Mikoto is mentioned as the father of {{ill|Ikatsu no Mikoto|ja|伊賀津臣|12=draft|12=draft}} (also known as Nakatomi no Ikatsu).
The *{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|12=draft|12=draft}}* records him as the thirteenth-generation descendant of Tsuhayatama no Mikoto and the tenth-generation descendant of {{ill|Ame-no-Koyane|ja|天児屋根命|1=Ame-no-Koyane|12=draft|12=draft}}, identifying him as the progenitor of the {{ill|Nakatomi Sakado clan|ja|中臣酒人宿祢|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Nakatomi Takara clan|ja|中臣高良比連|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>"Kawachi Province, Kami-betsu, Tenjin Line," *Shinsen Shōjiroku*, 806 CE.</ref><ref>"Sakyō Province, Kami-betsu, Tenjin Line," *Shinsen Shōjiroku*, 806 CE.</ref>
He is also enshrined as an auxiliary deity at {{ill|Sayama Shrine|ja|狭山神社|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Genealogy == Omi Sayama no Mikoto is identified as the son of {{ill|Kunimoro no Ōkashima no Mikoto|ja|国摩大鹿島命|12=draft|12=draft}}. His child is {{ill|Rai Daijin no Mikoto|ja|雷大臣命|12=draft|12=draft}}, who is noted as a significant ancestor in the Nakatomi lineage.<ref>*{{ill|Sonpi Bunmyaku|ja|尊卑分脈|12=draft|12=draft}}</ref><ref>Matsuo Shrine Genealogy (in *{{ill|Zoku Gunsho Ruijū|ja|続群書類従|12=draft|12=draft}}*, vol. 181).</ref>
== Related Articles == * {{ill|Urabe clan|ja|占部氏|1=Urabe clan|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Fudoki|ja|風土記|12=draft|12=draft}}
